he articulatory configurations seen in the examples are those of voiced post-alveolar nasals and fricatives. From the examples, a nasal is seen in “mon orange” and a fricative is seen in “nous avons”. For the fricative, the tongue is contacting the post-alveolar ridge and the vocal folds are adducted and vibrating. For the post-alveolar nasal, the tongue and vocal folds are configured in the same manner, but now the velum is lowered to allow air into the nasal cavity.  %0a%3c %0a%3c Source: %0a%3c https://www.linguisticsociety.org/sites/default/files/e-learning/09%252007%25202019%2520LECTURE.pdf%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: A:)%0a%3c (:Category: PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
